Source Code Free to Distribute under GPL License

================================================================================
                          BUILD & INSTALLATION GUIDE
================================================================================

OVERVIEW
--------
gslmon is a daemon written in Go that monitors Linux software RAID (mdadm) and
hardware RAID (megaraid pass-through) arrays. It checks kernel logs, /proc/mdstat,
and SMART disk health data, sending HTML email alerts when issues are detected.

Features:
  - Kernel log monitoring via journalctl for RAID/disk error patterns
  - /proc/mdstat polling for array state changes (degraded, recovering, etc.)
  - Periodic SMART long self-tests with automated result checking
  - RAID rebuild progress tracking with visual progress bar emails
  - Alert cooldown to prevent email flooding
  - Megaraid pass-through support for hardware RAID controllers
  - PID file locking to prevent duplicate instances
  - State persistence across daemon restarts

PREREQUISITES
-------------
  - Go 1.21 or later (for compilation)
  - smartmontools (provides smartctl)
  - mdadm (for software RAID monitoring)
  - systemd (for journalctl log access and service management)
  - An SMTP server accessible from the host (for sending alerts)

================================================================================
                       INSTALLING GO COMPILER
================================================================================

Ubuntu / Debian:
  sudo apt update
  sudo apt install -y golang-go smartmontools mdadm

  If the distro Go version is too old (<1.21), install from the official tarball:
  wget https://go.dev/dl/go1.22.5.linux-amd64.tar.gz
  sudo rm -rf /usr/local/go
  sudo tar -C /usr/local -xzf go1.22.5.linux-amd64.tar.gz
  export PATH=$PATH:/usr/local/go/bin

Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) 8/9:
  sudo dnf install -y golang smartmontools mdadm

CentOS Stream 8/9:
  sudo dnf install -y golang smartmontools mdadm

AlmaLinux 8/9:
  sudo dnf install -y golang smartmontools mdadm

  If Go is not available in default repos (RHEL/CentOS 8):
  sudo dnf install -y epel-release
  sudo dnf install -y golang

Rocky Linux 8/9:
  sudo dnf install -y golang smartmontools mdadm

Fedora:
  sudo dnf install -y golang smartmontools mdadm

openSUSE / SLES:
  sudo zypper install go smartmontools mdadm

Arch Linux:
  sudo pacman -S go smartmontools mdadm

================================================================================
                           COMPILATION
================================================================================

Clone the repository:
  git clone https://github.com/hawkeye4iot/gslmon.git
  cd gslmon

Build the binary:
  go build -o gslmon main.go

Build with optimizations (smaller binary, no debug symbols):
  go build -ldflags="-s -w" -o gslmon main.go

Verify the build:
  ./gslmon
  (Should print: "Usage: gslmon <config.json>")

Cross-compile for different architectures:
  GOOS=linux GOARCH=amd64 go build -ldflags="-s -w" -o gslmon-amd64 main.go
  GOOS=linux GOARCH=arm64 go build -ldflags="-s -w" -o gslmon-arm64 main.go

================================================================================
                           INSTALLATION
================================================================================

1. Copy the binary:
   sudo cp gslmon /usr/local/bin/
   sudo chmod 755 /usr/local/bin/gslmon

2. Create configuration directory and files:
   sudo mkdir -p /etc/gslmon
   sudo cp config.json.example /etc/gslmon/config.json
   sudo chmod 640 /etc/gslmon/config.json

3. Edit the configuration:
   sudo vi /etc/gslmon/config.json

   Update the following fields:
   - email.smtp_server    : Your SMTP server hostname
   - email.smtp_port      : SMTP port (typically 25 or 587)
   - email.from           : Sender email address
   - email.to             : Alert recipient email address
   - email.server_name    : Hostname used in SMTP HELO and alert subjects
   - raid.array_device    : Your RAID array device (e.g., /dev/md0)
                            Leave empty "" for hardware RAID only
   - raid.array_name      : Array name as shown in /proc/mdstat (e.g., md0)
   - raid.member_disks    : List of member disk devices to monitor via SMART
   - log_file             : Path for gslmon log output
   - state_file           : Path for daemon state persistence
   - tmp_dir              : Path for temporary files
   - pid_file             : Path for PID lock file

   For hardware RAID (e.g., Dell PERC / MegaRAID), set disk type:
   "member_disks": [
       {"device": "/dev/bus/0", "type": "megaraid,0", "name": "Disk 0"},
       {"device": "/dev/bus/0", "type": "megaraid,1", "name": "Disk 1"}
   ]

4. Create runtime directories:
   sudo mkdir -p /var/log/gslmon
   sudo mkdir -p /var/lib/gslmon/tmp
   sudo mkdir -p /var/run/gslmon

5. Install the systemd service:
   sudo cp gslmon.service /etc/systemd/system/
   sudo systemctl daemon-reload

6. Start and enable the service:
   sudo systemctl start gslmon
   sudo systemctl enable gslmon

7. Verify it is running:
   sudo systemctl status gslmon
   tail -f /var/log/gslmon/gslmon.log

================================================================================
                      CONFIGURATION REFERENCE
================================================================================

Email Configuration:
  smtp_server                    SMTP relay hostname
  smtp_port                      SMTP port (25 for unencrypted, 587 for STARTTLS)
  from                           Sender address for alert emails
  to                             Recipient address for alert emails
  server_name                    Server identifier in email subjects and HELO

RAID Configuration:
  array_device                   MD array device path (empty for HW RAID only)
  array_name                     Array name in /proc/mdstat
  raid_level                     RAID level description (raid1, raid10, etc.)
  mount_point                    Filesystem mount point of the array
  member_disks[].device          Disk device path for SMART queries
  member_disks[].type            SMART device type (empty for direct, "megaraid,N")
  member_disks[].name            Human-readable disk name for reports

Monitoring Configuration:
  log_check_interval_seconds     How often to scan kernel logs (default: 30)
  mdstat_check_interval_seconds  How often to poll /proc/mdstat (default: 3600)
  smart_test_interval_days       Days between SMART long self-tests (default: 2)
  smart_check_interval_hours     Hours between SMART health checks (default: 6)
  rebuild_check_interval_minutes Minutes between rebuild progress checks (default: 30)
  alert_cooldown_minutes         Minimum minutes between repeated alerts (default: 15)
  log_patterns                   Regex patterns to match in kernel logs
  smart_critical_attribute_ids   SMART attribute IDs flagged as critical

SMART Critical Attribute IDs (defaults):
  5   - Reallocated Sectors Count
  10  - Spin Retry Count
  171 - SSD Program Fail Count
  172 - SSD Erase Fail Count
  184 - End-to-End Error
  187 - Reported Uncorrectable Errors
  188 - Command Timeout
  197 - Current Pending Sector Count
  198 - Offline Uncorrectable
  199 - UDMA CRC Error Count
  201 - Soft Read Error Rate

================================================================================
                         UNINSTALLATION
================================================================================

  sudo systemctl stop gslmon
  sudo systemctl disable gslmon
  sudo rm /etc/systemd/system/gslmon.service
  sudo systemctl daemon-reload
  sudo rm /usr/local/bin/gslmon
  sudo rm -rf /etc/gslmon
  sudo rm -rf /var/log/gslmon
  sudo rm -rf /var/lib/gslmon
  sudo rm -rf /var/run/gslmon
